TY  - JOUR
AU  - Yamamoto, Yuichi
T1  - Individual Learning and Cooperation in Noisy Repeated Games
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdt029
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 81
IS  - 1
SP  - 473
EP  - 500
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We investigate whether two players in a long-run relationship can maintain cooperation when the details of the underlying game are unknown. Specifically, we consider a new class of repeated games with private monitoring, where an unobservable state of the world influences the payoff functions and/or the monitoring structure. Each player privately learns the state over time but cannot observe what the opponent learned. We show that there are robust equilibria in which players eventually obtain payoffs as if the true state were common knowledge and players played a “belief-free” equilibrium. We also provide explicit equilibrium constructions in various economic examples.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdt029
ER  - 



